# Datatable exports must use one key scheme end-to-end

Any Vue component that exposes `getExportConfig()` to `useDatatableFeatures`
(PDF/CSV/Excel) MUST return `columns` and `data` where every cell can be looked
up as `row[columns[i]]`. If the keys diverge, the composable's `formatCell`
falls through to `""` and exports render empty rows (as happened on the Fund
Type page — PDF header showed raw keys like `descMalay`, all rows blank).

The same invariant applies to in-view Excel exporters (e.g.
`FundTypeView.exportExcel`) that consume `cfg.columns` and `cfg.data`. Do NOT
use a `toLowerCase()` / alternate-key fallback to paper over a mismatch — fix
the source.

## ✅ Correct pattern

```ts
// In the child datatable component (e.g. FundTypeSmartFilterTable.vue)
function getExportConfig(): DatatableExportConfig | null {
  const exportColKeys = visibleColumns.value
    .map((c) => c.key)
    .filter((k) => k !== "no" && k !== "action");

  const keyToLabel: Record<string, string> = {
    fundType: "Fund Type",
    descMalay: "Description (Malay)",
    // ...
  };
  const keyToValue: Record<string, (r: Row) => string | number> = {
    fundType: (r) => r.ftyFundType ?? "",
    descMalay: (r) => r.ftyFundDesc ?? "",
    // ...
  };

  const columns = exportColKeys.map((k) => keyToLabel[k] ?? k);
  const data = sortedRows.value.map((r) => {
    const row: Record<string, unknown> = {};
    exportColKeys.forEach((k) => {
      const label = keyToLabel[k] ?? k;
      row[label] = keyToValue[k]?.(r) ?? "";
    });
    return row;
  });

  return { columns, data }; // columns[i] === every Object.keys(data[n])[i]
}
```

```ts
// Excel consumer in the view — single lookup, no fallback gymnastics
data.forEach((row, idx) => {
  const values = columns.map((c) => (row[c] ?? "") as string | number);
  ws.addRow([idx + 1, ...values]);
});
```

## ❌ Avoid

- `columns` built from one scheme (column keys) while `data` is keyed by
  another (spaces/lowercase) — causes empty PDF/CSV/Excel rows.
- `labelsMap` keyed by the data keys while `columns` uses column keys —
  `labelsMap[exportCol]` silently returns `undefined`.
- Excel exporters that try `row[c.toLowerCase()] ?? row[c]` to patch over a
  key mismatch. Fix `getExportConfig()` instead.

## Every export button must actually do something

Recurring regression on list pages: one or more of the PDF / CSV / Excel /
Add buttons renders but has no `@click` handler, or has no `type="button"`
and accidentally submits. Treat this as a checklist item, not optional.

```html
<!-- ✅ GOOD: all four footer buttons wired + explicit type -->
<button type="button" @click="handleDownloadPDF">PDF</button>
<button type="button" @click="handleDownloadCSV">CSV</button>
<button type="button" @click="exportExcel">Excel</button>
<button type="button" @click="openCreate">Add</button>
```

```html
<!-- ❌ BAD: seen in CostCentreView — Excel button had no handler,
     PDF/CSV/Add had no `type="button"`, so the browser defaulted to
     `type="submit"` and PDF silently stopped firing. -->
<button @click="handleDownloadPDF">PDF</button>
<button><FileSpreadsheet />Excell</button>
```

## Export columns must cover every visible data column

`defaultExportColumns` + `getFilteredList()` (or the child's
`getExportConfig()`) MUST include every non-`No`/non-`Action` column that the
datatable renders. Exporting a strict subset surprises users ("PDF looks
wrong / data missing"). This has regressed twice already — **Cost Centre**
(exported 4 of 9 columns) and **Cascade Structure** (exported 5 of 9, all
`*Desc` columns missing from PDF/CSV). Do NOT ship a list page where the
export column count is smaller than the visible table's data column count.
Build the list once and share it:

```ts
const exportColumns = [
  "Code", "Description (Malay)", "Description (English)",
  "PTJ", "PTJ Description", "Address", "Hostel Code", "Status",
];

function toExportRow(r: Row): Record<string, string | number> {
  return {
    Code: r.ccrCostcentre ?? "",
    "Description (Malay)": r.ccrCostcentreDesc ?? "",
    // ... one key per exportColumns entry, same labels
  };
}

useDatatableFeatures({
  defaultExportColumns: exportColumns,
  getFilteredList: () => rows.value.map(toExportRow),
  // ...
});

async function exportExcel() {
  // reuse exportColumns + toExportRow — NEVER re-declare columns here
  rows.value.forEach((r, idx) => {
    const row = toExportRow(r);
    ws.addRow([idx + 1, ...exportColumns.map((c) => row[c] ?? "")]);
  });
}
```

Reusing `exportColumns` + `toExportRow` across PDF/CSV/Excel is how you
guarantee the three formats stay in sync — no divergent column lists, no
drift when a new column is added to the table.

## Self-check before shipping any `list of ...` page

- [ ] `columns` and `Object.keys(data[0])` are element-wise equal.
- [ ] `exportColumns` covers every visible data column on the datatable
      (excluding `No` and `Action`).
- [ ] PDF / CSV / Excel / Add buttons each have `type="button"` and a
      non-empty `@click` handler. No dead buttons.
- [ ] PDF / CSV / Excel all use the same `exportColumns` + row-mapper
      (don't re-declare columns inside `exportExcel`).
- [ ] Hiding a column removes it from both `columns` and each `data` row.
- [ ] PDF header shows the human label (e.g. "Description (Malay)"), never
      the raw key (`descMalay`).
- [ ] Smoke-tested PDF, CSV and Excel with ≥1 row — values populated,
      column count matches the on-screen datatable.

Reference: `client/src/components/fims/FundTypeSmartFilterTable.vue` →
`getExportConfig()`; `client/src/views/CostCentreView.vue` and
`client/src/views/CascadeStructureView.vue` →
`exportColumns` + `toExportRow` + `exportExcel` (canonical shared-list pattern);
`client/src/composables/useDatatableFeatures.ts` →
`handleDownloadPDF` / `handleDownloadCSV` / `formatCell`.
